      <h2>The Problem</h2>
      <p>
        Therapists and clients share a fundamental problem: they have almost no shared
        visibility into whether therapy is working. Sessions happen in rooms. Notes
        stay in charts. Progress — or the absence of it — lives only in memory
        and subjective impression.
      </p>
      <p>
        This isn't a minor inconvenience. Research consistently shows that patients who
        track their own outcomes during treatment have better results — not because
        tracking is curative, but because it creates a feedback loop between session
        and daily life. When clients can see their own patterns, and therapists can
        see them too, something changes.
      </p>
      <p>
        The problem wasn't awareness. The tools didn't exist. Paper mood logs are
        compliance nightmares. Generic apps aren't built for therapeutic relationships.
        The shared visibility layer — the thing that could close the loop between
        session and daily life — didn't exist.
      </p>

      <h2>What I Built</h2>
      <p>
        Healify is a behavioral health platform built around one idea: therapist and
        client should be able to look at the same data together. A client logs their
        mood, energy, sleep, and context daily — not as a journaling exercise, but as
        a structured signal. The therapist sees that data, over time, in the session.
      </p>
      <p>
        The data model was designed from the start as user-partitioned and
        privacy-first. Clients own their data. Therapists access it through an explicit
        sharing relationship. Nothing moves without consent; nothing persists beyond
        its intended scope. The privacy architecture wasn't an afterthought — it was
        the reason clients would use it at all.
      </p>
      <p>
        Over time, the platform scaled to deliver over one million mood assessments.
        Clients who used it consistently reported a 260% increase in satisfaction
        with their therapeutic relationships. That number surprised me. I expected
        a compliance lift. I didn't expect it to affect the relationship itself.
      </p>

