      <h2>The Turn</h2>
      <p>
        In 2023, I made a decision that felt strange at the time: I stepped away from
        the product to practice as a somatic therapist. Not to research users. Not to
        run a discovery sprint. To actually treat people — chronic pain, anxiety, trauma
        — using hypnotherapy and nervous system regulation techniques.
      </p>
      <p>
        I treated over a hundred patients over the following year. And I learned things
        that no user research method had taught me.
      </p>
      <p>
        The first thing I learned: resistance isn't a design problem. When a client
        doesn't log their mood, or cancels their session, or agrees to something in
        the room and then doesn't do it — that's not a UX failure. That's the body
        doing exactly what bodies do. The nervous system protects. It avoids. It
        rationalizes. No amount of notification design changes that.
      </p>
      <p>
        The second thing I learned: the therapeutic relationship is the intervention.
        The data, the assessments, the tools — they're scaffolding. What actually
        moves people is feeling seen, over time, by someone who knows their patterns
        better than they do. That's what the shared data creates. Not measurement
        for its own sake, but context for the relationship.
      </p>
      <p>
        The third thing: most digital health tools are built around the model of
        individual behavior change. Do the thing. Track the thing. Get the reward.
        That model works for simple habits. It breaks down completely for anything
        involving the nervous system, trauma, or chronic pain — because the loop
        isn't behavioral. It's relational.
      </p>

      <h2>The Rebuild</h2>
      <p>
        In 2025, I rebuilt Healify from scratch. Not a redesign — a rethink of what
        the product was for.
      </p>
      <p>
        The original platform was built around measurement. The rebuild is built around
        the therapeutic relationship. The difference sounds subtle. It isn't.
      </p>
      <p>
        Key changes in the 2025 version:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Assessment is contextual, not scheduled.</strong> The original Healify
          sent daily reminders. The rebuild surfaces check-ins at moments of relevance —
          after a session, during a reported rough patch, at a cadence set by the therapist
          for each client individually.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Therapist-side tooling is first-class.</strong> The original product was
          client-facing with a thin dashboard for therapists. The rebuild inverts this:
          the therapist's view is the primary surface. Client data is presented in the
          context of the relationship arc, not as a raw feed.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Pattern recognition over point-in-time data.</strong> Single mood scores
          mean almost nothing. Patterns — across weeks, across contexts, across sessions —
          mean everything. The platform now surfaces those patterns explicitly, in language
          a therapist can use in session.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Privacy architecture hardened.</strong> The 2025 rebuild uses a
          fully user-partitioned Firestore model with explicit scope-limited access
          tokens for each therapist-client pair. Data doesn't aggregate across
          relationships. Nothing is retained after the relationship ends without
          explicit client action.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Technical Architecture</h2>
      <p>
        Healify is built on Google Firestore with a user-partitioned data model —
        every client's data lives in their own namespace, and therapist access is
        scoped to specific sharing tokens. The frontend is a progressive web app
        with offline support for mood logging in low-connectivity environments.
      </p>
      <p>
        The 2025 rebuild introduced a pattern-analysis layer using the Claude API.
        After a sufficient data window, the system generates natural-language
        summaries of client patterns — flagging anomalies, surfacing recurring
        themes, and highlighting changes in baseline. These summaries go to the
        therapist, not the client. The therapist decides what to do with them.
      </p>
      <p>
        That design decision — AI-assisted pattern recognition delivered to the
        practitioner, not the patient — came directly from clinical experience.
        Patients who receive algorithmic assessments of their own mental state
        frequently anchor to them in unhelpful ways. Therapists can contextualize.
        They can decide when the pattern insight is useful and when it's a distraction.
      </p>

      <h2>What I'd Do Differently</h2>
      <p>
        I would have practiced clinically before building the first version.
        Not as a research method — as a prerequisite. You can do all the user
        interviews you want. You cannot replicate the understanding that comes
        from sitting with someone in acute distress, watching how they move
        between insight and avoidance, and learning where the leverage actually is.
      </p>
      <p>
        The first version of Healify was a well-designed product that solved a
        real problem. The second version is a tool I would actually give to my
        own patients. That difference came entirely from clinical practice.
        It did not come from the product work.
      </p>

